subSubSection.paragraph:
ruficornis Kröber
( 1911 :
498 male
key, 520 orig. desc.; 1913 : 33 dist.; 1928 : 7 dist.),
Stuardo­Ortiz ( 1946 : 87 cat.)
(
Psilocephala
); (
Metz et al. 2003
: 244 comb. change, 245 : trans. orig. desc.) (
Notiothereva
). Type locality Chile , Concepción. Holotype male in Hermann Collection, presumed lost (
Metz et al. 2003
: 244 ). New synonomy.

No distinct characteristics were provided in the description of
Psilocephala ruficornis Kröber
that would clearly separate this species from
Notiothereva albventris (Philippi)
. This species shares with
N. albiventris
the femora being dark brown to black with white setae; the tibiae and tarsi being yellowish brown with darkened tips; the wings pterostigma dark brown to black, distinct; and cell m 3 being closed. The type locality was given as Concepción, Chile , which falls within the distribution pattern of
N. albiventris
(
Fig. 44
). Kröber named this species for the light reddish yellow first flagellomere of the antenna. Although this character is generally dark brown in
N. albiventris
, there is some variability with this character.

Diagnosis. Like
Notiothereva aurea
and
N. simulata
in having the frontal setae extending lateral to antennal base; parafacial with setae; and gena lacking anterodorsal patch of short, dark setae. It is similar to
N. aurea
in having dorsocentral macrosetae; halter dark brown; tibia dark yellow, apex dark reddish brown; setae on frons and parafacial predominately white; and cell m 3 closed. It differs from
N. aurea
in having mesonotal setae white and dark brown intermixed with appressed, short, gold setae; setae on scutellum white; cervical sclerite lacking setae; and the setae on male sternite 8 (
Fig. 3
) continuous across posterior margin.

subSubSection.paragraph: Redescription of male.
Body length 7.0– 8.2 , 7.5 mm .

Head. Length 0.94–1.16 , 1.07 mm . Frons pruinescence gray, dense (occasionally white); setae white (occasionally intermixed with black setae, occasionally pale brown), elongate, extending lateral to antennal base. Antenna dark brown, pruinescence gray, dense on scape; antenna/head length 0.6–0.9 , 0.7 ; scape length 0.24–0.34 , 0.28 mm , width 0.12–0.16 , 0.14 mm , length/width 1.7–2.5 , 2.1 , scape/pedicel length 2.3–3.8 , 2.9 , scape/ flagellum width 0.7 –1.0, 0.8 , setae white, elongate; pedicel length 0.08–0.12 , 0.10 mm , length/width 0.6 –1.0, 0.8 , setae dark reddish brown, short intermixed with dark yellow setae; flagellum length 0.35–0.42 , 0.39 mm , width 0.14–0.19 , 0.16 mm , length/width 2.2–2.9 , 2.4 , flagellum/scape length 1.1–1.7 , 1.4 . Parafacial pruinescence white (occasionally pale brown), dense; setae white. Maxillary palpus yellow to yellowish brown, pruinescence white; length 0.36–0.56 , 0.48 mm , length/width 6.0– 9.3 , 7.6 ; setae white. Genal setae white, lacking anterodorsal patch of short, dark setae. Occipital setae white; macrosetae dark brown, scattered at end of postocular macrosetae.

Thorax. Macrosetae 2–3 np, 2 sa, 1 pa, 2 dc, 2 sc. Mesonotum dark brown, pruinescence brownish gray; vittae indistinct; setae white, elongate intermixed with erect, elongate, dark brown setae and appressed, short, gold setae. Postpronotal lobe setae white. Cervical sclerite lacking setae. Pleuron pruinescence gray, dense; setae white, elongate on propleuron, anepisternum, katepisternum, laterotergite, scutellum, and metanepisternum. Wing. Membrane opaque, generally lacking maculation (occasionally brown marking at rm, fork of Rs, R 4 + 5 , apical margin of cells br , bm , and d ); venation pale brown; m 3 closed, petiolate (occasionally open widely); length 5.5–6.5 , 6.0 mm, length/width 2.5–2.9 , 2.7 ; pterostigma brown; cell cup closed, petiolate (occasionally open slightly). Halter knob dark brown. Legs. Coxa pruinescence white, dense; setae white, elongate; apical macrosetae dark reddish brown. Femora dark reddish brown (occasionally black), pruinescence white; ventral setae white on fore­ and midfemora; ad 0:0:0, av 2–4 : 2–3 : 4–7 , pv 0:0: 2–4 . Tibiae dark yellowish brown, apex dark reddish brown. Tarsomere 1 dark yellowish brown, apex dark reddish brown; 2–5 dark reddish brown.
Similar to male except for following.
Body length 6.8–8.8 , 7.8 mm .

Head. Length 0.96–1.28 , 1.12 mm . Frons pruinescence gray, setae dark brown dorsally, white ventrally and lateral to antennal base (occasionally yellowish brown; occasionally intermixed with black setae). Antenna/head length 0.58–0.75 , 0.65 ; scape length 0.24–0.28 , 0.26 mm , width 0.12–0.16 , 0.14 mm , length/width 1.7 –2.0, 1.9 , scape/ pedicel length 2.4–3.5 , 2.9 , scape/flagellum width 0.7–0.9 , 0.8 ; pedicel length 0.08–0.10 , 0.09 mm , length/width 0.6–0.9 , 0.7 ; flagellum length 0.36–0.40 , 0.37 mm , width 0.16–0.20 , 0.18 mm , length/width 1.9–2.4 , 2.1 , flagellum/scape length 1.4–1.6 , 1.4 . Maxillary palpus length 0.36–0.58 , 0.50 mm , length/width 6.0–7.0, 6.2 .
Thorax. Macrosetae 2–3 np, 1–2 sa, 1 pa, 2 dc, 2 sc. Wing. Length 5.3–6.8 , 6.1 mm , length/width 2.6–3.1 , 2.8 . Legs. Anterodorsal macrosetae 0:0:0, av 3–4 : 2–3 : 2–6 , pv 0:0: 2–6 .

Abdomen. Cuticle dark reddish brown, yellow posterolaterally and across posterior margin of tergites 2–4 , pruinescence gray, denser on tergite 5 ; dorsal setae dark reddish brown, appressed on dark reddish brown areas of abdomen, white across posterior margin of tergites 1–4 ; lateral setae white on tergites 1–3 , dark reddish brown on remaining tergites.
Terminalia
(MEI 147411 ). Furca (
Fig. 8
) quadrate, sides rounded; length 0.46 mm , width 0.26 mm ; anterolateral projection short.
Immature stages. Unknown.

Distribution.
Notiothereva albiventris
is known from
Argentina
and Chile (
Fig. 44
). Habitats and Temporal Phenology.
Notiothereva albiventris
has been hand­netted in a dry wash; collected in Malaise traps set on a hillside draw, in
Nothofagus
forest, in a damp wash, along a swift stream, on dry plains, and in a gully; and collected in pan and pitfall traps. Adults have been collected from October to April, but most abundantly in November and December.

Specimens Examined.
Type specimen.
The lectotype male of
Thereva albiventris
is labeled "Santiago, Chile " ( MNNC ). Other specimens. Numerous duplicate specimens of
N. albiventris
were collected by M. E. Irwin at various localities. Complete information on the total number of specimens collected by M. E. Irwin can be obtained from the author.
